.\" Manual page for tacctl, the tacquito management CLI.
.\" Render locally with: groff -man -Tascii man/tacctl.1 | less
.TH TACCTL 1 "2026-04-17" "tacctl" "Tacquito Control Manual"
.SH NAME
tacctl \- management CLI for the tacquito TACACS+ server
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B tacctl
.I command
.RI [ subcommand ]
.RI [ arguments... ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B tacctl
is a shell-based management CLI for
.BR tacquito ,
a TACACS+ server (RFC 8907).
It installs and upgrades the server, manages users and groups, edits
server configuration, inspects logs and backups, and generates ready-to-paste
device configuration for Cisco IOS/IOS-XE and Juniper Junos.
.PP
Most commands require root.
.B tacctl
re-executes itself under
.BR sudo (8)
automatically when invoked by a non-root user.
.B tacctl hash
and
.B tacctl version
are deliberate exceptions: they run as the invoking user.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS System lifecycle
.TP
.BI "install [--branch " name "]"
Install the tacquito server and supporting configuration. Installs the
Go toolchain, builds the tacquito binary, creates the
.B tacquito
service user, seeds
.IR /etc/tacquito/tacquito.yaml ,
installs the systemd unit, and enables the service. The optional
.BI --branch " name"
flag selects a specific tacctl repository branch for the install.
.TP
.BI "upgrade [--branch " name "]"
Pull the latest tacquito source and management scripts, rebuild the
binary if changed, refresh system files, and restart the service.
User-set flags for
.BR -network ,
.BR -address ,
and
.B -level
are preserved via a systemd drop-in so they survive template updates.
.TP
.B uninstall
Remove the tacquito service, binaries, configuration, logs, and
management repository. Offers to preserve backups and accounting logs
by archiving them to
.IR /root/ .
.TP
.B status
Show service health, authentication statistics, recent errors, and
password-age warnings.
.TP
.BR "version" ", " "--version" ", " "-v"
Print the tacctl version. The version is derived from
.BR git-describe (1)
against the installed repository, so it reflects the exact commit
currently deployed.
.SS User management \fB(tacctl user)\fR
.TP
.B user list
List all users with name, group, status, and password age.
.TP
.BI "user show " name
Show detailed user info: group, status, password change date and age,
last login (from the accounting log), Cisco privilege level, Juniper
class, and a hash fingerprint. Read-only -- does not prompt for the
password (unlike
.BR "user verify" ).
.TP
.BI "user add " "name group " [ "--hash " hash ]
Add a user. Prompts for the password with confirmation. If
.BI --hash " hash"
is given, the bcrypt hash is used directly and no password is prompted
(use this when users self-generate a hash; see
.BR "tacctl hash commands" ).
.TP
.BI "user remove " name
Remove a user after confirmation.
.TP
.BI "user passwd " "name " [ "--hash " hash ]
Change a user's password. Prompts for the new password with
confirmation. If
.BI --hash " hash"
is given, the bcrypt hash is used directly and no password is prompted
(mirrors
.B user add --hash
for users who self-generate via
.BR "tacctl hash commands" ).
.TP
.BI "user disable " name
Disable a user while preserving the password hash for later re-enable.
.TP
.BI "user enable " name
Re-enable a previously disabled user.
.TP
.BI "user rename " "old new"
Rename a user.
.TP
.BI "user move " "name group"
Move a user to a different group without changing the password.
.TP
.BI "user verify " name
Show user details and verify the password interactively.
.SS Group management \fB(tacctl group)\fR
.TP
.B group list
List all groups with Cisco privilege level, Juniper class, and user count.
.TP
.BI "group add " "name priv-lvl juniper-class"
Add a custom group.
.I priv-lvl
is an integer 0\(en15;
.I juniper-class
matches the Junos login class name.
.TP
.B "group edit " \fIname\fR " { priv-lvl \fIN\fR | juniper-class \fICLASS\fR }"
Change a group's Cisco privilege level or Juniper class. The built-in
groups
.RB ( readonly ,
.BR operator ,
.BR superuser )
can be edited but not removed.
.TP
.BI "group remove " name
Remove a custom group. Built-in groups are protected.
.TP
.B "group commands list " \fIgroup\fR
Show the per-command authorization rules for a group, including the
default action (the action of the trailing
.RB ` * `
catchall rule).
.TP
.B "group commands default " \fIgroup\fR " { permit | deny }"
Set the default action for unmatched commands. Stored as the action
of a trailing
.RB ` * `
rule that tacquito's
.B CommandBasedAuthorizer
matches as a wildcard.
.TP
.B "group commands add " \fIgroup\fR " " \fIname\fR " [ --match \fIregex\fR ]... [ --action permit | deny ]"
Append a rule. Default action is
.BR permit .
The
.I name
is matched against the TACACS+
.B cmd=
field literally. Each
.B --match
adds an arg-list regex (auto-anchored with
.RB ` ^…$ `).
The first matching rule wins; tacquito returns FAIL if no rule
matches and the
.RB ` * `
catchall is not
.BR permit .
.TP
.B "group commands remove " \fIgroup\fR " " \fIname\fR
Drop a rule by name. The
.RB ` * `
catchall is protected; change it via
.B group commands default
or remove the entire block via
.B group commands clear .
.TP
.BI "group commands clear " group
Wipe all command rules for a group (with confirmation). When other
groups at the same Cisco privilege level still have rules, this
group's users will be denied all commands at that level until you
re-add a catchall (or clear those siblings too).
.TP
.B "group commands seed " [ \fIgroup\fR ] " " [ --force ]
Populate the built-in groups
.RB ( readonly ,
.BR operator ,
.BR superuser )
with sensible default rule sets. Without an argument, seeds all three;
with a group name, seeds only that one (custom groups are not seeded).
Refuses to overwrite an existing
.B commands:
section unless
.B --force
is given. Defaults:
.B readonly
permits
.IR "show ping traceroute terminal exit end quit logout who where enable"
with default deny;
.B operator
adds
.IR "clear test monitor"
to the readonly set with default deny;
.B superuser
gets a
.RB ` "* permit" `
catchall (unrestricted).
.TP
.BI "group privilege list " group
Show the Cisco
.B "privilege exec level"
mappings for a group. Reports whether the source is an explicit
override (in
.IR /etc/tacquito/cisco-privileges.conf )
or the built-in default set (move-DOWN commands only).
.TP
.B "group privilege add " \fIgroup\fR " '\fIcommand\fR'"
Move a Cisco command to the group's priv-lvl. Quote multi-word
commands (e.g.
.RB ' "show running-config" ' ).
On first
.B add
the group's defaults are inherited; subsequent adds extend that set.
.TP
.B "group privilege remove " \fIgroup\fR " '\fIcommand\fR'"
Drop a previously-mapped command. If only defaults are in effect, the
remove takes effect against the default set (suppressing it for that
group).
.TP
.BI "group privilege clear " group
Wipe explicit mappings for a group; the built-in default set takes
over again.
.TP
.B "group privilege seed " [ \fIgroup\fR ] " " [ --force ]
Populate the built-in groups with their default mapping set. Same
shape as
.BR "group commands seed" .
Default sets:
.B readonly
none (priv-1 is the floor);
.B operator
.RI ' "show running-config" '
and
.RI ' "show startup-config" '
moved DOWN from priv-15;
.B superuser
none (priv-15 is the ceiling).
.PP
Cisco devices enforce these rules LIVE — once any group has rules,
.B tacctl config cisco
emits
.B aaa authorization commands 1/7/15 default group TACACS-GROUP local
and IOS asks tacquito for every command. Juniper enforces locally via
class
.B allow-commands
/
.B deny-commands
regex; a per-device config push is required after every change.
.SS Server configuration \fB(tacctl config)\fR
.TP
.B config show
Show the current configuration summary.
.TP
.B config validate
Validate config syntax and structure.
.TP
.BI "config diff " [ timestamp ]
Diff the current config against a backup. Defaults to the most recent
backup.
.TP
.BI "config secret " [ value ]
Change the TACACS+ shared secret. If no value is given, a random
hex-only secret is generated. Hex-only secrets avoid shell-quoting
issues on devices.
.TP
.BI "config loglevel " [ debug | info | error ]
Show or change the server log level. Written to a systemd drop-in so
the change survives upgrades.
.TP
.B "config listen " "{ show | tcp | tcp6 | reset } " [ address ]
Show, change, or reset the TCP listen address. Stored in the drop-in
at
.IR /etc/systemd/system/tacquito.service.d/tacctl-overrides.conf .
.B reset
clears the override and falls back to the template default.
.B
Switching to tcp6
prompts for confirmation because dual-stack sockets accept IPv4
clients via mapped addresses
.RB ( ::ffff:x.x.x.x )
that silently bypass IPv4 prefix ACLs; see
.B NOTES.
.TP
.B "config sudoers " "{ show | install | remove } " [ group ]
Manage the optional
.I /etc/sudoers.d/tacctl
drop-in that grants NOPASSWD sudo on
.B tacctl
to a group (default:
.BR adm ).
Installs are validated with
.BR visudo (8)
before taking effect. Not installed by default.
.TP
.BI "config password-age " [ days ]
Show or set the password age warning threshold. Default 90 days.
.TP
.BI "config bcrypt-cost " [ "10-14" ]
Show or set the bcrypt cost factor used when hashing new or changed
passwords. Default 12. Existing hashes keep their minted cost.
.TP
.BI "config password-min-length " [ "8-64" ]
Show or set the minimum length enforced by
.B validate_password_strength
on interactively-entered passwords. Default 12 (OWASP 2025). Floor 8
(NIST 800-63). Auto-generated passwords (operator accepts the blank
prompt) bypass this check.
.TP
.BI "config secret-min-length " [ "16-128" ]
Show or set the minimum length enforced when an operator types a
custom shared secret via
.BR "config secret" .
Default 16 (Cisco TACACS+ best practice). Auto-generated secrets
bypass this check.
.TP
.B "config prefixes " "{ list | add | remove | clear } " [ cidr ]
Manage the secret-provider's client-prefix list. These are the CIDRs
the shared secret is bound to — connections from outside any listed
prefix can't authenticate. Adds and removes are dedup-aware and
restart the service.
.B clear
empties the list (and prompts for confirmation, since it makes the
shared secret unreachable).
.TP
.BI "config prefixes " [ "cidr,cidr,..." ]
(Legacy form.) With no arguments, prompts interactively for a
comma-separated replacement list. With a comma-list, replaces the
entire prefixes block in one atomic write. Equivalent to
.B "config prefixes clear"
followed by repeated
.B "config prefixes add"
calls.
.TP
.B "config allow " "{ list | add | remove } " [ cidr ]
Manage the connection allow list (IP ACL).
.TP
.B "config deny " "{ list | add | remove } " [ cidr ]
Manage the connection deny list.
.B deny
takes precedence over
.BR allow ;
with both empty, all connections are accepted.
.TP
.B "config mgmt-acl " "{ list | add | remove | clear } " [ cidr ]
Manage a shared CIDR permit list stored at
.I /etc/tacquito/mgmt-acl.conf
that drives both the Cisco VTY-ACL and a commented Juniper lo0
firewall-filter example emitted by
.B config cisco
and
.BR "config juniper" .
Preserved across
.BR "tacctl upgrade" .
With no arguments, prints usage and the current entry count.
.TP
.BI "config mgmt-acl cisco-name " [ name ]
Show or set the name of the IOS access-list emitted by
.BR "config cisco" .
Default
.BR VTY-ACL .
Names must start with a letter and contain only letters, digits,
.RB ` _ ` ,
or
.RB ` - `
(max 63 chars).
.TP
.BI "config mgmt-acl juniper-name " [ name ]
Show or set the name of the Junos firewall filter emitted by
.BR "config juniper" .
Default
.BR MGMT-SSH-ACL .
Same character rules as
.BR cisco-name .
Both overrides live at
.I /etc/tacquito/mgmt-acl-names.conf
and survive
.BR "tacctl upgrade" .
.TP
.B config cisco
Print a ready-to-paste Cisco IOS/IOS-XE configuration with the
server IP, shared secret, current group-to-privilege mappings, and
the VTY-ACL built from
.B config mgmt-acl
pre-filled.
.TP
.B config juniper
Print a ready-to-paste Juniper Junos configuration with template
users, TACACS+ server setup, verification commands, and a commented
lo0 firewall-filter example built from
.B config mgmt-acl
pre-filled.
.TP
.BI "config branch " [ name ]
Show or change the tacctl repository branch used by
.B tacctl upgrade.
.SS Log inspection \fB(tacctl log)\fR
.TP
.BI "log tail " [ n ]
Show the last
.I n
journal entries for the tacquito service (default 20).
.TP
.BI "log search " term
Search logs for a username or keyword over the last 7 days.
.TP
.B log failures
Show authentication failures from the last 24 hours.
.TP
.BI "log accounting " [ n ]
Show the last
.I n
entries from
.IR /var/log/tacquito/accounting.log .
.SS Backup management \fB(tacctl backup)\fR
.TP
.B backup list
List available config backups with timestamps.
.TP
.BI "backup diff " [ timestamp ]
Diff the current config against a backup (default: most recent).
.TP
.BI "backup restore " timestamp
Restore a config backup after confirmation.
.PP
Backups are created automatically before every change. The last 30 are
retained under
.IR /etc/tacquito/backups/ .
.SS Hash generation \fB(tacctl hash)\fR
.TP
.B hash
With no subcommand (or with
.BR help ),
prints a usage summary listing
.B generate
and
.BR commands .
Does not require root.
.TP
.B hash generate
Interactively prompt for a password on the server and print its bcrypt
hash. Needs
.B python3-bcrypt
installed. Intended for admins who can shell in to the tacquito host.
.TP
.B hash commands
Print client-side bcrypt-generation recipes for operators who cannot
SSH to the server. Covers Linux/macOS (Python + htpasswd), Windows
(Python + PowerShell/BCrypt.Net), and any-OS Node.js. Each recipe
prints both the raw
.B $2b$\&...
and hex-encoded forms;
.B "user add --hash"
/
.B "user passwd --hash"
accept either and normalize to hex on write.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/tacquito/tacquito.yaml
TACACS+ server configuration. Mode 0640, owned by
.BR tacquito : tacquito .
.TP
.I /etc/tacquito/backups/
Automatic configuration backups. Last 30 retained.
.TP
.I /etc/tacquito/password-max-age
Custom password age warning threshold, in days. Optional.
.TP
.I /etc/tacquito/templates/
Host-specific overrides for the Cisco and Juniper device config
templates.
.TP
.I /etc/systemd/system/tacquito.service
Systemd unit file.
.TP
.I /etc/systemd/system/tacquito.service.d/tacctl-overrides.conf
Systemd drop-in where
.B "tacctl config listen"
and
.B "tacctl config loglevel"
write their overrides. Preserved across upgrades.
.TP
.I /etc/sudoers.d/tacctl
Optional NOPASSWD sudoers rule. Installed only via
.BR "tacctl config sudoers install" .
.TP
.I /var/log/tacquito/accounting.log
Per-session accounting records. Rotated daily, retained 90 days.
.TP
.I /usr/local/bin/tacquito
The tacquito server binary.
.TP
.I /usr/local/bin/tacctl
Symlink to
.IR /opt/tacctl/bin/tacctl.sh .
.TP
.I /usr/local/bin/tacquito-hashgen
Standalone bcrypt hash generator shipped with tacquito.
.TP
.I /opt/tacctl/
Clone of the management (tacctl) repository. Source of the symlinked
CLI and the source directory consulted by
.BR "tacctl upgrade" .
.TP
.I /opt/tacquito-src/
Clone of the tacquito server source code, used to rebuild the binary
during
.BR "tacctl upgrade" .
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Install on a fresh host:
.B sudo tacctl install
.TP
Add a superuser:
.B sudo tacctl user add alice superuser
.TP
Restrict allowed device subnets:
.B sudo tacctl config prefixes 10.1.0.0/24,172.16.5.0/24
.TP
Generate a Cisco-ready configuration to paste onto a switch:
.B sudo tacctl config cisco
.TP
Bind the listener to a specific management IP:
.B sudo tacctl config listen tcp 10.1.0.1:49
.TP
Enable passwordless invocation for members of the adm group:
.B sudo tacctl config sudoers install adm
.TP
Print client-side bcrypt generation instructions to share with a user:
.B tacctl hash commands
.SH NOTES
.B IPv4 only by default.
The service runs with
.B -network tcp
which binds IPv4 only. Switching to
.B tcp6
enables a dual-stack socket on most platforms; IPv4 clients then
connect with IPv4-mapped addresses
.RB ( ::ffff:10.1.0.1 )
that do not match IPv4 prefix ACLs configured via
.BR "tacctl config prefixes" ,
.BR "config allow" ,
or
.BR "config deny" .
Add equivalent IPv6 prefix rules before enabling
.B tcp6.
.PP
.B Juniper template users are required.
Every
.B local-user-name
referenced by a group class (for example
.BR RO-CLASS ,
.BR OP-CLASS ,
.BR RW-CLASS )
must have a matching local user on each Juniper device. Without this,
TACACS+ authentication succeeds but Junos rejects the login silently.
Run
.B tacctl config juniper
to regenerate the device-side configuration after adding or editing
groups.
.PP
.B Config edits.
.B tacctl
automatically restarts the service and creates a backup before every
change. Manual edits to
.I /etc/tacquito/tacquito.yaml
require
.B sudo systemctl restart tacquito
afterwards.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR systemctl (1),
.BR journalctl (1),
.BR visudo (8),
.BR tacquito (8)
.SH PROJECT
https://github.com/rett/tacctl
